      <!-- ══ CHAPTER I ════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <div class="chapter-row">
        <a class="chapter-marker" href="{{ "/thesis/chapter-1/" | url }}"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-1/" | url }}">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/title-pages/Chapter_1.png" | url }}"
               alt="Chapter I — A fixed set of rules — title page">
        </a>
        <div class="chapter-text-scroll">
          <div class="home-section"
               data-label="Chapter I — A fixed set of rules"
               data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-1/" | url }}"
               data-text="It seems that rules play an important part in the way I work. A system can be defined as a set of objects together with relationships between the objects and between their attributes.">
            It seems that rules play an important part in the way I work. When I start a work, I usually start with a question, a fascination or a problem. In most cases the solution brings another fixed set of rules in which I work. A system can be defined as a set of objects together with relationships between the objects and between their attributes. Hall and Fagen offer this definition which Ludwig von Bertalanffy adopted in his book General System Theory. A system consists of objects and the relations between them. The objects can have different attributes. An important element in the definition is that there are relations. There are always at least two elements in a relation. A single object is not yet a system. General Systems Theory is a science that studies the general concept of systems and aims to explain rules and principles that are valid for all types of systems. The aim is to show structural similarities in the different sciences. The idea is that the same kind of logical and mathematical laws apply for systems regardless of the domain of investigation. By seeking these similarities it can also show structural differences and make it possible to see where something from one domain can transfer to another domain and what might be the problems of such a transfer. The theory tries to build a bridge between the various disciplines.

            <span class="home-image-embed"
                  data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
                  title="Hans Haacke — Condensation Cube, 1963–65">
              <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/63_65condensationcube2_347x500jpg.jpg" | url }}"
                   width="52" height="75" alt="Hans Haacke, Condensation Cube">
              <span class="embed-caption">Haacke, 1963</span>
            </span>

            When reading the definition of a system it becomes clear that it can be an extremely broad definition. Everything can be, and actually is, a system. I think the definition is so broad because the aim is to find universal rules that can be applied across all systems regardless of what kind of system it is. Every system has an environment, the set of all objects a change in whose attributes affect the system and also those objects whose attributes are changed by the behaviour of the system. The environment then consists of all elements that are not part of the system but do have influence on it or are influenced by it. The environment and the system are always linked to each other. When you change the environment you also change the system and vice versa. Within every system there are subsets that can be seen as systems in themselves: subsystems. These can overlap. A subsystem can interact with the environment of the larger system. Everything can be seen as a subsystem of a larger system. An important distinction within systems theory is the one between open and closed systems. Closed systems are isolated from the environment. Open systems exchange matter with the environment, exhibit import and export, building-up and breaking-down of their material components. Most biological systems are open systems. They are in constant exchange with their environment. The notion of compatibility is used to describe how systems relate to each other. It addresses whether two or more systems can work together without conflict. In my work, I am often interested in what happens when two incompatible systems are brought together, or when a system is forced to operate in an environment for which it was not designed. What I find most useful in General Systems Theory is the idea that the same structural principles can apply across completely different domains. The theory gives me permission to make connections across disciplines, to see the same pattern in a scientific text and in a work of art, in a biological process and in a social structure.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ══ CHAPTER II ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <div class="chapter-row">
        <a class="chapter-marker" href="{{ "/thesis/chapter-2/" | url }}"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-2/" | url }}">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/title-pages/Chapter_2.png" | url }}"
               alt="Chapter II — A fixed set of rules on art — title page">
        </a>
        <div class="chapter-text-scroll">
          <div class="home-section"
               data-label="Chapter II — A fixed set of rules on art"
               data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-2/" | url }}"
               data-text="In 1968 Jack Burnham published Systems Aesthetics in Artforum, introducing the systems theory of Ludwig von Bertalanffy to the art world.">
            In 1968 Jack Burnham published Systems Aesthetics in Artforum. Burnham introduced the systems theory of Ludwig von Bertalanffy to the art world. He saw a fundamental shift happening in art away from the object toward systems. This essay was a groundbreaking text that tried to define this new kind of art making that he saw appearing in the late 1960s. The shift Burnham described was a shift from an object-oriented to a systems-oriented culture. Not the single isolated artwork but the system, the relations between objects and ideas, becomes the subject of art. Burnham positioned his ideas within the context of both Conceptual Art and the emerging field of Art-and-Technology. Conceptual Art had already started to question the primacy of the art object. Artists like Sol LeWitt, Lawrence Weiner and Joseph Kosuth had argued that the idea or concept behind a work is more important than the physical realisation. If the idea is there, the work exists, even without being physically made.

            <span class="home-image-embed"
                  data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
                  title="Dan Graham — Homes for America, 1966–67">
              <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/grahamhomes6667.jpg" | url }}"
                   width="68" height="48" alt="Dan Graham, Homes for America">
              <span class="embed-caption">Graham, 1966</span>
            </span>

            Burnham saw the concept of environment as central to understanding this new art. The environment is not just the physical space in which art is displayed but the entire context — including social and political conditions — in which the work is produced and received. The artwork is always part of a larger system and must be understood in relation to this larger system. This connects directly to von Bertalanffy's definition of environment: everything that is not part of the system itself but influences it. For Burnham, the art world — galleries, critics, collectors, institutions — is the environment of the artwork. Changing the environment changes what the artwork is and does. Conceptual Art as a movement was defined by its questioning of the traditional definition of art. If art could be an idea, then the boundaries of what art could be were dramatically expanded. The question became not what something is, but how it functions within a system of relations. Burnham was sympathetic to Conceptual Art but wanted to go further. For him, even the concept was not enough. What mattered was the system — the total set of relations within which the artwork exists and operates.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ══ CHAPTER III ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <div class="chapter-row">
        <a class="chapter-marker" href="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}">
          <img src="{{ "/assets/images/title-pages/Chapter_3.png" | url }}"
               alt="Chapter III — A fixed set of rules on art, explained by artworks — title page">
        </a>
        <div class="chapter-text-scroll">
          <div class="home-section"
               data-label="Chapter III — Explained by artworks"
               data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
               data-text="Burnham's key argument: the most important art of his time was not concerned with the production of objects but with the production of systems.">
            Burnham's key argument was that the most important art of his time was not concerned with the production of objects but with the production of systems. A Transition from an Object-Oriented to a System-Oriented Culture. The shift Burnham saw was happening everywhere in culture. In architecture, urban planning, music, and art, the emphasis was moving from the individual object to the system, from the single thing to the relationships between things. Dan Graham's Homes for America (1966–67) is a good example of this shift. Rather than making an object to hang on a gallery wall, Graham documented the system of suburban housing developments — the grid, the repetition, the logic of mass production applied to the home. The artwork is the system, not any single house. Art Does Not Reside in Material Entities. If art is fundamentally about systems and relationships, then it cannot be located in any single material object. The artwork is not the painting on the wall but the total system: the artist, the context, the viewer, the institution, the social relations. Hans Haacke's Condensation Cube (1963–65) makes this literal: the work is a closed system — a sealed acrylic cube in which water condenses and evaporates according to the temperature of the gallery space.

            <span class="home-image-embed"
                  data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
                  title="Martha Rosler — Bringing the War Home, 1967–72">
              <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Rosler.jpg" | url }}"
                   width="48" height="62" alt="Martha Rosler">
              <span class="embed-caption">Rosler, 1967</span>
            </span>

            <span class="home-image-embed"
                  data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
                  title="Mel Bochner — Measurement Room, 1969">
              <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Mel_Brochner_measurment_room.jpg" | url }}"
                   width="52" height="72" alt="Mel Bochner, Measurement Room">
              <span class="embed-caption">Bochner, 1969</span>
            </span>

            Art is Not Autonomous. Art is always embedded in a context, always part of a larger system of relations. Martha Rosler's photomontages make this point forcefully: by embedding images of the Vietnam War into the domestic interiors of House Beautiful, she shows that the domestic and the political are part of the same system. Art is Conceptual Focus. What art provides is a specific kind of attention, a way of focusing on particular systems and making them visible. Mel Bochner's Measurement Room (1969) does exactly this: by writing the dimensions of a room directly on its walls, he makes visible the system of measurement that is always already there but usually invisible. No Definition or Theory of Art Can Be Historically Unvarying. Because art is always embedded in its context and because contexts change, no single definition of art can be valid for all times.

            <span class="home-image-embed"
                  data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-3/" | url }}"
                  title="Robert Smithson">
              <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Smithson.jpg" | url }}"
                   width="68" height="48" alt="Robert Smithson">
              <span class="embed-caption">Smithson</span>
            </span>

            The approach I take in my work is informed by all of these ideas. I am interested in systems, in the relations between things, in how order is made and unmade. I do not believe in the autonomous artwork, but in the artwork as part of a larger system of relations. When I look at Robert Smithson's work, I see this too: the Spiral Jetty is a system, a feedback loop between the artwork, the landscape, time, and the viewer. Burnham was writing at a specific moment, and his claims need to be understood in relation to that moment. The 1960s were a period of enormous expansion in the definition of art. Happenings, Performance Art, Land Art, Conceptual Art, Arte Povera — all of these movements were questioning the traditional art object.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

