      <!-- ══ CHAPTER IV ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- Title page image not yet exported — using styled fallback -->
      <div class="chapter-row">
        <a class="chapter-marker" href="{{ "/thesis/chapter-4/" | url }}"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-4/" | url }}">
          <div class="chapter-marker-fallback">
            <span class="chapter-marker-fallback-num">Chapter IV</span>
            <span class="chapter-marker-fallback-title">Composition<br>of Thoughts</span>
          </div>
        </a>
        <div class="chapter-text-scroll">
          <div class="home-section"
               data-label="Chapter IV — Composition of Thoughts"
               data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-4/" | url }}"
               data-text="The concept of system is what ties together my practice. When I make work, I set up a system — a set of rules, a framework, a structure — and then I follow it.">
            Truth. The question of truth in art and in knowledge more broadly is central to my practice. I do not believe in a single truth, but in multiple truths that are always situated, always produced within specific contexts and relations. What is true within one system may not be true within another. This is not relativism — some truths are better, more precise, more useful than others — but it is a recognition that truth is always produced, always made. Unity. A system is unified in the sense that it holds together as a whole, but it is not homogeneous. Unity in diversity: the system holds together precisely because of the differences between its elements, not despite them. System. The concept of system is what ties together my practice. When I make work, I set up a system — a set of rules, a framework, a structure — and then I follow it. The system is the artwork, not the physical result. The physical result is just the trace of the system at work.

            <span class="home-image-embed"
                  data-url="{{ "/projects/stegen-van-harlingen/" | url }}"
                  title="Stegen van Harlingen — Lyske Gais">
              <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Vorm.jpg" | url }}"
                   width="42" height="75" alt="Stegen van Harlingen">
              <span class="embed-caption">Harlingen</span>
            </span>

            Aesthetic Enjoyment. The aesthetic dimension of the work is not separate from its conceptual dimension. The aesthetic experience is the experience of the system, the experience of the relations between things. When you encounter a work of mine, I want you to feel the system — to sense the structure, to see the order, and then to wonder what the order reveals. There is pleasure in finding order in apparent chaos. There is also pleasure in finding chaos in apparent order. Both are aesthetic experiences, and both are experiences of systems. Inspiration. Where does inspiration come from? For me, it comes from observation, from looking at the world and finding structures and systems in what I see. The world is full of systems, and making art is a way of making some of those systems visible. I am not inventing systems; I am finding them and making them visible. Perception. Perception is always structured. We do not see raw data but always already interpreted information, ordered and categorised by our perceptual and cognitive systems. What we see is a product of the systems through which we see.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ══ CHAPTER V ════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- Title page image not yet exported — using styled fallback -->
      <div class="chapter-row">
        <a class="chapter-marker" href="{{ "/thesis/chapter-5/" | url }}"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-5/" | url }}">
          <div class="chapter-marker-fallback">
            <span class="chapter-marker-fallback-num">Chapter V</span>
            <span class="chapter-marker-fallback-title">Finding<br>the Yellow Duck</span>
          </div>
        </a>
        <div class="chapter-text-scroll">
          <div class="home-section"
               data-label="Chapter V — Finding the Yellow Duck"
               data-url="{{ "/thesis/chapter-5/" | url }}"
               data-text="Structures and systems are everywhere. Orders are what make me see. When researching I think you shouldn't exclude anything — everything can be part of the work.">
            Structures and systems are everywhere. The element of resemblances versus differences is what Foucault describes as the tool to order. So on the one hand it is an intrinsic value of the object. On the other hand it is a value we have given to the thing and can only exist if there are also other things. If there would only be one thing, you wouldn't be able to order it. It is humans who make the whole systems and structures. It is something we impose on the world. It is our need to name and order the things. The relations or beautiful orders are what catch my eye and make it for a possible subject of a work. So it's not the actual order that is the subject. Orders are what make me see. Research (Gather). When researching I think you shouldn't exclude anything — everything can be part of the work. And when the research is at a point where finding the elements that make the work and/or story possible, I can lift them out and create the work around it. Plan (Order). Then, undoubtedly, I am stuck with this huge pile of things. By now I have usually managed to make a simple — although vague and intuitive — start with a very complex amount of stuff that from the outside is not quite related. The only way out is to put it all next to each other and get it all back in line. To order them, and by the order itself see what the main elements are.

            <span class="home-image-embed"
                  data-url="{{ "/projects/amsterdam/" | url }}"
                  title="Amsterdam — Lyske Gais">
              <img src="{{ "/assets/images/defff/Amsterdam.jpg" | url }}"
                   width="48" height="68" alt="Amsterdam overhemd">
              <span class="embed-caption">Amsterdam</span>
            </span>

            Execute (Do). Then comes the part of actually doing things. When I am making, I fix the system and do it, and do it, and do it again. I don't change during the making, because I think that if you do that you can't really judge the end result because you haven't been precise in doing it. The system is arbitrary throughout its development, but once the system of variables — the character — has been defined at the outset, it is no longer possible to modify it, to add or subtract even one element. Space. Art provides a space — similar to the one provided by language — in which things that cannot otherwise coexist can be juxtaposed. Both leave gaps to be filled by the viewer. The gaps might be different, but the fact that they create this unthinkable space is the same. Maybe in art it is not space, but concept or thought.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- ══ CONCLUSION ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
      <!-- Title page image not yet exported — using styled fallback -->
      <div class="chapter-row">
        <a class="chapter-marker" href="{{ "/thesis/conclusion/" | url }}"
           data-url="{{ "/thesis/conclusion/" | url }}">
          <div class="chapter-marker-fallback">
            <span class="chapter-marker-fallback-num">Conclusion</span>
            <span class="chapter-marker-fallback-title">Concluding That<br>Ducks Never<br>Remain Yellow</span>
          </div>
        </a>
        <div class="chapter-text-scroll">
          <div class="home-section"
               data-label="Concluding That Ducks Never Remain Yellow"
               data-url="{{ "/thesis/conclusion/" | url }}"
               data-text="The Yellow Duck is the theory on my art practice. The view I have created will not be permanent. It will change; I will change; the world will change.">
            The Yellow Duck is thus the theory on my art practice. A phenomenon is something that happens and you can observe it. Doing this thesis, I have studied texts in relation to my way of working. I have gathered what triggered my interest and seemed fitting to create a view on my work. And having learned from Burnham, this conclusion is tied to the here and now. It is a view I have achieved now, with the knowledge and the works I have created thus far and with a world that is at the beginning of the year 2012. I am aware that the view I have created will not be permanent. It will change; I will change; the world will change. The yellow duck I have found now will not stay yellow, or there can be another yellow duck hidden somewhere. It is not so strange that I have started this thesis with the element that I am actually using at the final part of a work: the system. The actual work is what remains and what you will remember best. Creating systems is a way to get some confidence or security into what I am doing, but this can be dangerous if I stop being aware of it. What I try to do is lift some connections up from the web of strings and make them visible for a short time. Sometimes to judge, sometimes just to show and tell and make you realise that the world is bigger and more complicated than we can comprehend in our day-to-day lives. Systems and structures are what tie the world together. There is no truth. And I don't mind.
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

